<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11067l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11067l">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11067l"> 67(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> potin / racontar / cancan / (quamquam)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Au moyen &acirc;ge, beaucoup de gens pronon&ccedil;aient le latin bonnement et, au lieu de dire comme nous <mark><i>quanquam</i>, ils disaient <i>cancan</i></mark>; tout le monde pourtant ne disait pas de la sorte: cela fit une querelle. On en rit, et le mot entra dans la langue vulgaire o&ugrave; il prit &agrave; peu pr&egrave;s le sens, qu&apos;il a aujourd&apos;hui, <mark>de &ldquo;potin&rdquo;, de &ldquo;racontar&rdquo;</mark>; bien entendu en fran&ccedil;ais, on l&apos;&eacute;crivit <i>cancan</i>. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Et le <i>Dictionnaire</i> acad&eacute;mique de 1835, Littr&eacute; m&ecirc;me admettent deux orthographes: <i>quanquans</i> et <i>cancans</i>. <font color="green">[In the middle-ages lots of people had a reasonable pronunciation of Latin, and instead of saying like us <i>quanquam</i>, they said <i>cancan</i>; but not everybody said it like that; so a quarrel broke out. This was joked about and the word was used in the vernacular where it took the meaning that it has today, of &ldquo;gossip&rdquo; and &ldquo;slander&rdquo;; but of course in French, one wrote it <i>cancan</i>.[&hellip;]</font> And the dictionary of the Acad&eacute;mie of 1835 and Littr&eacute; allow two orthographies: <i>quanquans</i> and <i>cancans</i>.] <small> Jacques Boulenger et Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="JBAT" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JBAT"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 92-3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
